title: For Sale/Trade:  New Custom AR-15. Top of the line, must see.
location: All around town, Texas, United States
postcontent: People, really? Its not custom if you piece all the parts together from whatever you can't find. Nor does it make it more valuable. You will never get your money back from something you bought retail. If you list your rifle higher in price than a LaRue tactical or an LWRC, you are smoking crack. I don't care what cool guy paint job you have or what shitty off brand scope or bipod you put on it, hell you could put everything you can find, I'm still only concerned about the rifle. Guys if you are looking for a rifle and don't know much about AR-15s ask, or look up forums. Spikes, bushmaster, DPMS, Olympus Arms, DEL-TON, these are all bottom of the barrel everyday lowers and uppers. Thats just a small list, I could go on. Nothing wrong with them, they work fine if you want a truck gun, plinker, SHTF, but by no means should you pay over $650 unless it was A LOT of high end after market parts, like name brand triggers, free float hand rails, compensators, and buttstock. Still I wouldn't pay over $1200-!400 depending on what you get. Do yourself a favor and look to buy a matching set, they usually fit better, i.e. upper and lower. I have built my own and guess what, I sold it cause it wasn't near as nice as my LaRue. AND i should it to a friend at a loss, right in the middle of the AR scare of 2013.

title: For Sale/Trade:  *** STOP Buying Over Priced Ammo and Guns!!!!! ***
postcontent:
People, 

Please stop buying over priced ammo and guns on this site... 

It is disgusting what some of you are asking people to pay for ammo that is now available in most stores and online. Seriously I was able to walk into Walmart the other day and they had 1000rd boxes of 22LR for $52.00, not $100.00 that I see people trying to sell here.  BTW - Dicks Sporting Goods, Bill Jacksons and Gander Mountain almost always have 22LR in stock you just have to ask because they do keep it behind the counter.

And some of the unrealistic prices I see on guns.... I am sorry but just because you bought a gun you don't like anymore, does not make it worth more than you paid. A gun is like a car it depreciates in value until it become a collectable, and not all do.... 

My best advice is to do some research before you buy firearm. A quick Internet search should tell you what the price is for a new gun and if it is lower than the price someone is trying to sell you a used one for.... well you get the point. 

Sorry to vent but I am tired of seeing these ridiculous prices.

postcontent:
This is the ultra rare Olympic arms 2.9 lb. 5.56 pistol. It has a skelentonized lower receiver, stainless steel 6" barrel, all top quality parts. This weapon has never been fired. 

A very large handgun based upon the M16 rifle. It has a special recoil spring and buffer, so that the usual long spring housing at the end of the frame is eliminated. Just like the M16 it fires the hardhitting 5.56 NATO cartridge, although its power is slightly diminished by the shorter barrel. This gun is made entirely from extruded aluminum, which helps greatly in keeping the ultimate weight down.

The gun typically comes standard with a ten round magazine, but of note is that any pre-Brady bill M16 magazine will fit. This means that, if you can find the magazines, you can fit 20 or 30 shot magazines in this gun without problems.
